              <tr><td>Useful for everyday writing</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes — core use case</td><td class="cell-no">No</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Real monthly cost for SEO outcomes</strong></td><td>Pair with $99/mo Surfer + writers</td><td><strong>$99 flat</strong></td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where Grammarly wins:</strong> any writing task where clarity and correctness matter (emails, docs, drafts, social). <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> generating ranked organic content end-to-end. Pick by the job, not the brand — and honestly, the two can coexist on the same monthly budget.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Grammarly?</h2>
        <p>Grammarly is an AI-powered writing assistant founded in 2009 by Alex Shevchenko, Max Lytvyn, and Dmytro Lider in Kyiv, Ukraine (now headquartered in San Francisco). It checks grammar, spelling, clarity, tone, and style in real-time across browsers, desktop apps, mobile keyboards, and 500,000+ third-party app integrations.</p>

        <p>The core suite does five things:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Grammar &amp; spelling</strong> — real-time corrections as you type</li>
          <li><strong>Clarity</strong> — rewrites long, vague, or hard-to-read sentences</li>
          <li><strong>Tone detection</strong> — flags emails that sound rude or uncertain</li>
          <li><strong>Plagiarism check</strong> — scans against 16B+ web pages and academic databases</li>
          <li><strong>GrammarlyGO (AI)</strong> — generates, rewrites, expands, summarizes</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Grammarly is <em>not</em>: an SEO tool, a content optimization scorer, or a publishing platform. It makes your writing clearer. It does not make it rank.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Grammarly is privately held with $400M+ raised at a $13B valuation. The company serves 30M+ daily active users and 70,000+ business teams. Revenue is estimated at $200–250M ARR. Headquartered in San Francisco with engineering teams in Kyiv, Vancouver, and New York.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">Grammarly features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The feature surface is broad and well-tested. Here's what actually matters in daily use.</p>

        <h3>1. Real-time grammar &amp; spelling</h3>
        <p>The foundation. Underlined suggestions appear as you type in Gmail, Google Docs, Word, Slack, LinkedIn, and almost everywhere else. Accuracy is the best in the industry — catches subject-verb agreement, comma splices, dangling modifiers, and homophone errors that other tools miss.</p>

        <h3>2. Clarity rewrites</h3>
        <p>Premium-only. Highlights long sentences, passive voice, weak word choices, and redundancy. Offers one-click rewrites that preserve meaning while cutting word count by 20–40%. The single most underrated feature in the product.</p>

        <h3>3. Tone detection</h3>
        <p>Reads your draft and tells you how it sounds — confident, casual, formal, friendly, urgent. Useful before sending sensitive emails. Less useful for blog content where tone is set in the brief.</p>

        <h3>4. Brand voice (Business + Enterprise)</h3>
        <p>Upload writing samples and Grammarly learns your house style. Suggestions then nudge writers toward your tone, vocabulary, and formality. Best feature on the Business tier — pays for itself if you have 5+ writers and care about brand consistency.</p>

        <h3>5. GrammarlyGO (AI assistant)</h3>
        <p>Bundled with Premium and Business. Generates first drafts, rewrites paragraphs, changes tone, expands or shortens. Output is competent but generic — about on par with raw ChatGPT for short-form work, weaker for long-form.</p>

        <h3>6. Plagiarism checker</h3>
        <p>Premium and Business. Scans against 16B+ web pages and ProQuest academic databases. Catches unintentional duplication reliably. Less sensitive than dedicated tools (Copyscape, Turnitin) but sufficient for most business use.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">Grammarly pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>
        <p>Grammarly publishes pricing. Here are the live numbers.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
